WEBVTT

00:22.421 --> 00:24.220
        (AIRPLANE WHIRRING)

00:26.023 --> 00:27.655
          (SHUTTER OPENING)

00:45.741 --> 00:47.841
      (PEOPLE CHATTERING)

00:51.646 --> 00:53.445
 Your first trip
 to London?

00:53.447 --> 00:54.779
                      Yes.

00:54.781 --> 00:56.080
 You want
 a word of advice?

00:56.082 --> 01:00.818
 Don't trust the cab drivers.
 They'll take you five miles
 to go three blocks.

01:00.820 --> 01:04.221
 And don't waste your time
 looking at a street map.

01:04.223 --> 01:09.292
 Nobody can find
 their way around London,
 not even Londoners.

01:09.294 --> 01:11.594
        Maybe I should go
        to Baltimore instead?

01:11.596 --> 01:14.630
           No, you'll enjoy it.

01:15.566 --> 01:17.332
 London's a great place.

01:17.334 --> 01:21.269
 What kind of trip is it,
 business or pleasure?

01:21.571 --> 01:24.071
           Unfinished business.

02:38.380 --> 02:40.546
                   (INDISTINCT)

03:20.721 --> 03:22.554
          Taxi!

03:26.860 --> 03:28.226
 Where to, luv?

03:28.228 --> 03:30.328
        84 Charing Cross Road.

03:30.330 --> 03:31.862
 Come on in.

03:53.385 --> 03:57.286
      <i> (MAN SPEAKING ON TV)</i>

04:23.547 --> 04:28.116
 <i> HELENE: "Gentlemen.</i>
 <i> Your ad in the</i>
 Saturday Review of Literature

04:28.118 --> 04:33.721
    <i> "says that you specialize</i>
    <i> in out-of-print books."</i>

04:34.523 --> 04:35.455
 They're all
 pretty uncommon.

04:35.457 --> 04:38.624
   Anyone would think I was
   asking for Isaiah's personal
   copy of the Old Testament.

04:38.626 --> 04:41.793
         These are famous books
         by famous writers
         for God's sake!

04:41.795 --> 04:44.896
 They're British books
 by British writers.

04:44.898 --> 04:46.964
 Nobody asks for them
 anymore.

04:46.966 --> 04:47.965
 Maybe you should try
 Scribner's.

04:47.967 --> 04:52.302
       I've been to Scribner's.
       Everything is so fancy
       over there.

04:52.304 --> 04:53.803
            Haven't you got any
            cheap editions?

04:53.805 --> 04:57.840
 Some, but not the ones
 you want. I'm sorry.

04:58.676 --> 05:01.843
   This is the fourth bookstore
   I've been to this morning.

05:01.845 --> 05:06.214
     Doesn't anybody read
     English literature
     in New York?

05:19.696 --> 05:21.962
  <i> Saturday Review.</i>

05:37.279 --> 05:40.146
   <i> HELENE: "October 5, 1949.</i>

05:40.148 --> 05:44.617
      <i> "To Marks & Co.,</i>
      <i> 84 Charing Cross Road.</i>

05:44.619 --> 05:48.954
      <i> "London WC2, England.</i>

05:48.956 --> 05:52.357
     <i> "Gentlemen. Your ad</i>
     <i> in the</i> Saturday Review
     of Literature

05:52.359 --> 05:56.761
     (TYPEWRITER CLACKING)
  <i> "says that you specialize</i>
  <i> in out-of-print books.</i>

05:56.763 --> 06:01.565
    <i> "The phrase</i>
    <i> 'antiquarian bookseller'</i>
    <i> scares me somewhat</i>

06:01.567 --> 06:04.434
      <i> "as I equate 'antique'</i>
      <i> with 'expensive.'</i>

06:04.436 --> 06:07.870
 <i> "I'm a poor writer with</i>
 <i> an antiquarian taste in books,</i>

06:07.872 --> 06:11.206
   <i> "and all the things I want</i>
   <i> are impossible</i>
   <i> to get over here,</i>

06:11.208 --> 06:14.509
    <i> "except in very expensive,</i>
    <i> rare editions.</i>

06:14.511 --> 06:17.311
    <i> "I enclose a list of</i>
    <i> my most pressing problems.</i>

06:17.313 --> 06:21.214
 <i> "If you have any clean,</i>
 <i> second-hand copies of</i>
 <i> any of the books on the list,</i>

06:21.216 --> 06:26.085
   <i> "for no more than $5 each,</i>
   <i> will you consider this</i>
   <i> a purchase order</i>

06:26.087 --> 06:27.653
     <i> "and send them to me?</i>

06:27.655 --> 06:33.525
        <i> "Very truly yours,</i>
        <i> Helene Hanff."</i>

06:36.162 --> 06:38.529
                "Dear madam.

06:39.665 --> 06:42.298
       "In reply to your letter

06:42.300 --> 06:43.699
           "of October the 5th,

06:43.701 --> 06:49.471
   "we have managed to clear up
   two-thirds of your problem.

06:52.442 --> 06:53.541
                "The three
                Hazlitt essays
                you want

06:53.543 --> 07:00.147
     "are contained in
     the Nonesuch Press edition
     of his <i> Selected Essays,</i>

07:01.583 --> 07:05.351
             "and the Stevenson
             is found in

07:05.486 --> 07:09.688
       <i> "Virginibus Puerisque."</i>

07:17.364 --> 07:21.165
   <i> FRANK: "We're sending</i>
   <i> nice copies of both these</i>
   <i> by book post</i>

07:21.167 --> 07:24.401
   <i> "and trust they will arrive</i>
   <i> safely in due course</i>

07:24.403 --> 07:27.270
  <i> "and that you will be pleased</i>
  <i> with them.</i>

07:27.272 --> 07:30.673
     <i> "Our invoice is enclosed</i>
     <i> with the books.</i>

07:30.675 --> 07:33.575
   <i> "The Leigh Hunt essays</i>
   <i> are not going to be so easy,</i>

07:33.577 --> 07:38.379
   <i> "but we will see if we can</i>
   <i> find an attractive volume</i>
   <i> with them all in.</i>

07:38.381 --> 07:43.217
  <i> "We haven't the Latin Bible</i>
  <i> you describe, but we have</i>
  <i> a Latin New Testament,</i>

07:43.219 --> 07:50.624
  <i> "also a Greek New Testament.</i>
  <i> Ordinary modern editions</i>
  <i> in cloth binding.</i>

07:50.626 --> 07:58.732
     <i> "Would you like these?</i>
     <i> Yours faithfully, FPD,</i>
     <i> for Marks & Co."</i>

08:05.107 --> 08:07.807
        (PHONE RINGING)

08:08.910 --> 08:11.310
         Helene Hanff.
         Hi, Maxine.

08:11.312 --> 08:12.210
  <i> (WOMAN CHATTERING ON PHONE)</i>

08:12.212 --> 08:16.547
 Oh, sweetheart, look,
 I can't talk now. I slept
 through my alarm this morning.

08:16.549 --> 08:17.948
         Okay, fine.

08:17.950 --> 08:21.084
       Call you later.
       Bye-bye.

08:28.827 --> 08:31.594
             (HUMMING)

08:48.613 --> 08:55.884
 <i> HELENE: "14 East 95th Street,</i>
 <i> New York City.</i>
 <i> November 3, 1949.</i>

08:55.886 --> 08:57.886
          <i> "Gentlemen.</i>

08:57.888 --> 08:58.820
   <i> "The books arrived safely.</i>

08:58.822 --> 09:04.458
   <i> "The Stevenson is so fine</i>
   <i> it embarrasses my</i>
   <i> orange-crate bookshelves.</i>

09:04.460 --> 09:09.362
<i> "I'm always afraid</i>
<i> to handle such soft vellum</i>
<i> and heavy cream-colored pages.</i>

09:09.364 --> 09:14.767
 <i> "Being used to the dead-white</i>
 <i> paper and stiff cardboardy</i>
 <i> covers of American books,</i>

09:14.769 --> 09:19.872
      <i> "I never knew a book</i>
      <i> could be such a joy</i>
      <i> to the touch."</i>

09:24.078 --> 09:26.111
                  Brian!

09:29.749 --> 09:31.582
                 Brian!

09:31.584 --> 09:33.850
 In here!

09:34.986 --> 09:36.585
           Hi, Helene.
                           Hi.

09:36.587 --> 09:39.888
        I thought
        I'd find you
        in here.

09:40.457 --> 09:43.224
      Come on, we're
      going to be late.

09:43.226 --> 09:44.058
 Won't be a minute.

09:44.060 --> 09:46.794
    <i> HELENE: "A Britisher</i>
    <i> whose girl lives upstairs,</i>

09:46.796 --> 09:52.900
 <i> "translated the one pound</i>
 <i> 17 shillings, sixpence for me,</i>

09:52.902 --> 09:57.004
    <i> "and says I owe you</i>
    <i> $5.30 for the two books."</i>

09:57.006 --> 09:58.638
                  Are you sure
                  that's right?

09:58.640 --> 10:00.673
     Hang on.
     Let me check.

10:00.675 --> 10:01.373
          Uh...

10:01.375 --> 10:07.245
 One pound, 17 and 6,
 that's 37 and a half
 shillings, divided by...

10:07.413 --> 10:12.282
      Yes, that's right.
      $5.30.

10:16.087 --> 10:18.620
     <i> HELENE: "I enclose</i>
     <i> a $5 bill and a single.</i>

10:18.622 --> 10:23.124
    <i> "Please use the 70 cents</i>
    <i> towards the price of</i>
    <i> the New Testaments,</i>

10:23.126 --> 10:24.158
     <i> "both of which I want.</i>

10:24.160 --> 10:26.894
    <i> "Will you please translate</i>
    <i> prices hereafter?</i>

10:26.896 --> 10:28.262
      <i> "I don't add too well</i>
      <i> in plain American.</i>

10:28.264 --> 10:32.666
     <i> "I haven't a prayer</i>
     <i> of ever mastering</i>
     <i> bilingual arithmetic.</i>

10:32.834 --> 10:36.202
     <i> "Yours, Helene Hanff."</i>

10:41.909 --> 10:46.544
 I hope "madam"
 doesn't mean over there
 what it means over here.

10:46.612 --> 10:48.011
                  Huh.

10:53.351 --> 10:58.721
              Helene Hanff.
              She's sent us
              six dollars.

10:58.723 --> 11:00.989
             And 70 cents over.

11:00.991 --> 11:04.826
    I suppose that would be...
    Five, five and six.

11:04.828 --> 11:06.661
                           Yes.

11:08.464 --> 11:09.930
                 (SNIGGERING)

11:11.967 --> 11:16.602
    <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>
    <i> Your six dollars</i>
    <i> arrived safely.</i>

11:16.604 --> 11:20.772
 <i> "But we should feel</i>
 <i> very much easier if you would</i>
 <i> send your remittances</i>

11:20.774 --> 11:23.174
      <i> "by postal money order</i>
      <i> in the future,</i>

11:23.176 --> 11:24.942
       <i> "as this would be</i>
       <i> a bit safer for you</i>

11:24.944 --> 11:30.013
  <i> "than entrusting dollar bills</i>
  <i> to the mails.</i>

11:32.117 --> 11:35.251
   <i> "We're very happy you liked</i>
   <i> the Stevenson so much.</i>

11:35.253 --> 11:37.286
        <i> "We have sent off</i>
        <i> the New Testaments</i>

11:37.288 --> 11:43.425
  <i> "with an invoice</i>
  <i> listing the amount due</i>
  <i> in both pounds and dollars.</i>

11:43.427 --> 11:46.294
     <i> "And we hope you will be</i>
     <i> pleased with them."</i>

11:46.296 --> 11:48.129
                    (WHISTLING)

11:48.464 --> 11:52.466
      <i> HELENE: (ANGRILY)</i>
      <i> "What kind of a black</i>

11:52.468 --> 11:56.870
   <i> "Protestant Bible is this?</i>

12:01.243 --> 12:01.741
                 (SIGHING)

12:01.743 --> 12:03.008
      <i> "Kindly inform</i>
      <i> the Church of England</i>

12:03.010 --> 12:07.145
   <i> "that they have loused up</i>
   <i> the most beautiful prose</i>
   <i> ever written.</i>

12:07.147 --> 12:10.882
      <i> "Who ever told them</i>
      <i> to tinker with</i>
      <i> the</i> Vulgate Latin?

12:10.884 --> 12:14.619
      <i> "They'll burn for it,</i>
      <i> mark my words.</i>

12:14.621 --> 12:16.420
       <i> "It's nothing to me.</i>
       <i> I'm Jewish myself.</i>

12:16.422 --> 12:20.390
   <i> "But I have</i>
   <i> a Catholic sister-in-law,</i>
   <i> a Methodist sister-in-law,</i>

12:20.392 --> 12:22.992
     <i> "a whole raft</i>
     <i> of Presbyterian cousins</i>

12:22.994 --> 12:25.728
   <i> "through my great uncle</i>
   <i> Abraham, who was converted,</i>

12:25.730 --> 12:28.197
   <i> "and an aunt who's</i>
   <i> a Christian Science healer.</i>

12:28.199 --> 12:32.701
<i> "And I'd like to think</i>
<i> none of them would countenance</i>
<i> this Anglican Latin Bible</i>

12:32.703 --> 12:40.141
   <i> "if they knew it existed.</i>
   <i> As it happens, they</i>
   <i> don't know Latin existed.</i>

12:46.048 --> 12:50.850
      <i> "I enclose $4 to cover</i>
      <i> the $3.88 due you.</i>

12:50.852 --> 12:53.786
  <i> "Buy yourself a cup of coffee</i>
  <i> with the 12 cents.</i>

12:53.788 --> 12:56.755
<i> "There's no post office</i>
<i> near here, and I'm not running</i>
<i> all the way down</i>

12:56.757 --> 13:01.126
    <i> "to Rockefeller Plaza</i>
    <i> to stand in line</i>
    <i> for a $3.88 money order.</i>

13:01.128 --> 13:03.561
     <i> "If I wait</i>
     <i> till I get down there</i>
     <i> for something else,</i>

13:03.563 --> 13:07.264
        <i> "I won't have</i>
        <i> the $3.88 anymore.</i>

13:07.266 --> 13:08.131
     <i> "I have implicit faith</i>

13:08.133 --> 13:13.870
       <i> "in the US Airmail</i>
       <i> and His Majesty's</i>
       <i> Postal Service.</i>

13:13.872 --> 13:17.440
    <i> "Have you got a copy</i>
    <i> of Landor's</i>
    Imaginary Conversations?

13:17.442 --> 13:18.874
        <i> "I think there are</i>
        <i> several volumes.</i>

13:18.876 --> 13:21.843
    <i> "The one I want</i>
    <i> is the one with</i>
    <i> the Greek conversations.</i>

13:21.845 --> 13:25.847
    <i> "If it contains a dialogue</i>
    <i> between Aesop and Rhodope,</i>

13:25.849 --> 13:27.815
      <i> "that'll be the volume</i>
      <i> I want."</i>

13:27.817 --> 13:31.518
          That, I think,
          is the one we've got.

13:32.053 --> 13:33.285
                  Cecily,

13:33.287 --> 13:39.291
      Landor,
      <i> Imaginary Conversations.</i>
      Dig it out, would you?

13:45.198 --> 13:49.066
       (BELLS RINGING)
       <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>
       <i> Your $4 arrived safely</i>

13:49.068 --> 13:53.437
  <i> "and we have credited</i>
  <i> the 12 cents to your account.</i>

13:53.439 --> 13:58.341
 <i> "We happen to have in stock</i>
 <i> Volume 2 of</i> The Works and
 Life of Walter Savage Landor,

13:58.343 --> 14:03.079
 <i> "which contains the</i>
 <i> Greek dialogues including the</i>
 <i> one mentioned in your letter,</i>

14:03.081 --> 14:05.848
       <i> "as well as</i>
       <i> the Roman dialogues.</i>

14:05.850 --> 14:08.350
      <i> "It is an old edition</i>
      <i> published in 1876,</i>

14:08.352 --> 14:12.854
      <i> "not very handsome,</i>
      <i> but well bound and</i>
      <i> a good clean copy.</i>

14:12.856 --> 14:18.326
     <i> "And we are sending</i>
     <i> it off to you today</i>
     <i> with invoice enclosed.</i>

14:18.394 --> 14:21.261
 <i> "I'm sorry we made the mistake</i>
 <i> with the Latin Bible,</i>

14:21.263 --> 14:23.696
      <i> "and we'll try to find</i>
     <i> a</i> Vulgate <i> for you.</i>

14:23.698 --> 14:26.465
  <i> "Not forgetting Leigh Hunt.</i>

14:28.602 --> 14:33.638
     <i> "Yours faithfully, FPD,</i>
     <i> for Marks & Co."</i>

14:36.376 --> 14:38.509
            Ah, thank you.

15:01.066 --> 15:03.633
        Very nice.
        Very tasty.

15:38.036 --> 15:38.634
         <i> HELENE: "Sir.</i>

15:38.636 --> 15:41.370
   <i> "It feels witless to keep</i>
   <i> writing 'Gentlemen' when</i>
   <i> the same solitary soul</i>

15:41.372 --> 15:44.639
    <i> "is obviously taking care</i>
    <i> of everything for me.</i>

15:44.641 --> 15:49.010
 <i> "Savage Landor arrived safely</i>
 <i> and promptly fell open</i>
 <i> to a Roman dialogue</i>

15:49.012 --> 15:52.279
       <i> "where two cities</i>
       <i> had just been</i>
       <i> destroyed by war</i>

15:52.281 --> 15:56.049
    <i> "and everybody was being</i>
    <i> crucified and begging</i>
    <i> passing Roman soldiers</i>

15:56.051 --> 15:58.384
       <i> "to run them through</i>
       <i> and end the agony.</i>

15:58.386 --> 16:00.853
    <i> "It'll be a relief to turn</i>
    <i> to Aesop and Rhodope,</i>

16:00.855 --> 16:04.489
   <i> "where all you have</i>
   <i> to worry about is a famine.</i>

16:04.491 --> 16:05.923
                 (COUGHING)

16:09.361 --> 16:14.097
 <i> "I do love second-hand books</i>
 <i> that open to the page some</i>
 <i> previous owner read oftenest.</i>

16:14.099 --> 16:18.367
  <i> "The day Hazlitt came,</i>
  <i> he opened to,</i>
  <i> 'I hate to read new books.'</i>

16:18.369 --> 16:23.538
  <i> "And I hollered, 'Comrade!'</i>
  <i> to whoever owned it</i>
  <i> before me.</i>

16:23.540 --> 16:26.607
<i> "I enclose a dollar,</i>
<i> which Brian, British boyfriend</i>
<i> of Kay upstairs,</i>

16:26.609 --> 16:32.679
  <i> "says will cover</i>
  <i> the 8 shillings I owe you.</i>
  <i> You forgot to translate it."</i>

16:39.054 --> 16:41.254
              (CHATTERING)

16:54.502 --> 16:56.335
            Thank you.

16:58.005 --> 16:59.604
           Only two this week
           per family, luv.

16:59.606 --> 17:05.443
  <i> HELENE: "Now then. Brian</i>
  <i> told me you are all rationed</i>
  <i> to two ounces of meat</i>

17:05.444 --> 17:09.914
     <i> "per family per week</i>
     <i> and one egg per person</i>
     <i> per month!</i>

17:09.915 --> 17:11.882
  <i> "And I am simply appalled."</i>

17:11.884 --> 17:15.285
            Somebody told Brian
            about this firm
            in Denmark.

17:15.287 --> 17:18.054
                 They ship
                 food packages
                 to England.

17:18.056 --> 17:20.156
     I used them
     to send food
     to my mother.

17:20.157 --> 17:21.624
                Show her
                the catalog.

17:21.626 --> 17:24.792
 They're very reliable
 and cheap too.

17:24.795 --> 17:27.929
    Well, cheapish.

17:30.934 --> 17:34.468
                  Oh, my God!
                  Look at this!

17:34.470 --> 17:34.968
        (ALL LAUGHING)

17:34.970 --> 17:38.404
                   They've got
                   spiced lard,
                   liver paste,

17:38.406 --> 17:39.438
                     meatballs,

17:39.440 --> 17:44.309
       chocolate shortcake,
       margarine, eggs, cheese.

17:44.311 --> 17:45.410
              Well, they've got
              everything!

17:45.412 --> 17:49.080
 Brian's mother said she
 couldn't believe her eyes when
 she saw the first package.

17:49.082 --> 17:50.314
                   What did you
                   send her?

17:50.316 --> 17:51.515
       Tin of ham.
       Some sausages.

17:51.517 --> 17:54.551
             KAY: Tinned fruit.
  Tinned fruit, plums,
  raspberries.

17:54.553 --> 17:56.519
     "Rahz-berries," don't you
     just love that?

17:56.521 --> 17:59.321
       Imagine, a whole country
       says "rahz-berries!"

17:59.323 --> 18:00.722
 (IMITATING COWBOY)
 BRIAN: They sure do, ma'am!

18:00.724 --> 18:04.092
                 Rahz-berries,
                 rahz-berries,
                 rahz-berries.

18:04.094 --> 18:05.760
              HELENE: Look,
              this is terrific.

18:05.762 --> 18:08.829
             Let's make a list.
             Hold that.

18:09.631 --> 18:10.262
    Where shall we start?

18:10.264 --> 18:11.563
          How about a ham?
          We got to send a ham.

18:11.565 --> 18:13.031
     A ham.
              It's Christmas!
              We'll send a ham.

18:13.033 --> 18:17.135
   How about some soup?
   Mulligatawny soup.
   They'd like that.

18:17.137 --> 18:18.202
      What else should we send?
            Biscuits.

18:18.204 --> 18:21.138
   Vegetables! What about
   vegetables? Some vegetables?
        Vegetables.

18:21.140 --> 18:23.273
 What don't they have?
               Carrots, peas...

18:23.275 --> 18:24.040
      Haricots verts.

18:24.042 --> 18:26.776
             HELENE: (LAUGHING)
             Haricots verts?
        KAY: How can we not?

18:26.778 --> 18:27.910
              HELENE: How about
              string beans?

18:27.912 --> 18:29.311
   There's two types of
   haricots verts,

18:29.313 --> 18:32.080
   there's the choicest
   or there's choice!

18:32.082 --> 18:35.349
 BRIAN: How about some...
             Bananas? Oh, let's
             send a banana!

18:35.351 --> 18:40.954
    <i> HELENE: "I'm sending it</i>
    <i> care of you, FPD,</i>
    <i> whoever you are.</i>

18:40.956 --> 18:43.423
      <i> "Noel, Helene Hanff."</i>
          Sheila,

18:43.425 --> 18:47.660
 could you pass me
 one of those cards
 to hang over the mirror?

18:47.662 --> 18:50.763
              The church or
              Father Christmas?

18:50.765 --> 18:51.330
    Which do you like?

18:51.332 --> 18:53.532
              Father Christmas.
     Yes. It's pretty.

18:53.534 --> 18:54.533
             NORA: How are you
             getting on?

18:54.535 --> 18:57.402
  FRANK: All right,
  I think.

18:57.404 --> 18:58.636
                    Grand.

18:58.638 --> 19:00.137
 What are you cooking?

19:00.139 --> 19:01.338
                 Mince pies.

19:01.340 --> 19:04.240
       Oh. Good.

19:05.610 --> 19:07.743
     How are you
     getting on there?

19:10.380 --> 19:15.483
 Sheila, pass me
 the holly. Be careful.
 Don't prick yourself.

19:15.852 --> 19:17.218
        Thank you.

19:18.254 --> 19:19.586
        (GRUNTS)

19:19.955 --> 19:20.753
                 (CHUCKLING)

19:20.755 --> 19:26.725
 Don't laugh. I'm bleeding.
 What are you laughing at?

19:28.395 --> 19:30.661
     <i> HELENE: "FPD! Crisis!</i>

19:30.663 --> 19:34.665
   <i> "I sent that package off,</i>
   <i> the chief item in it</i>
   <i> was a six-pound ham!</i>

19:34.667 --> 19:37.701
      <i> "I figured you could</i>
      <i> take it to a butcher</i>
      <i> and get it sliced up</i>

19:37.703 --> 19:41.271
  <i> "so everybody would have some</i>
  <i> to take home.</i>

19:41.273 --> 19:43.740
   <i> "But I just noticed on your</i>
   <i> last invoice, it says,</i>

19:43.742 --> 19:47.310
      <i> "'B. Marks, M. Cohen,</i>
      <i> Proprietors'.</i>

19:47.312 --> 19:51.480
   <i> "Are they kosher?</i>
   <i> I could rush a tongue over!</i>

19:51.482 --> 19:53.215
       <i> "Advise, please!"</i>

19:53.217 --> 19:54.583
            (EXHALING)

19:59.623 --> 20:00.321
    <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>

20:00.323 --> 20:05.492
  <i> "Just a note to let you know</i>
  <i> that your gift parcel</i>
  <i> arrived safely today."</i>

20:05.494 --> 20:06.125
              Pork sausages.

20:06.127 --> 20:09.895
 <i> "Mr. Marks and Mr. Cohen</i>
 <i> insisted that we divide it up</i>
 <i> among ourselves</i>

20:09.897 --> 20:13.064
  <i> "and not include the bosses.</i>

20:13.900 --> 20:16.667
    <i> "I should just</i>
    <i> like to add that</i>
    <i> everything in the parcel</i>

20:16.669 --> 20:18.001
     <i> "was something</i>
     <i> that we either never see</i>

20:18.003 --> 20:20.136
   <i> "or can only be had through</i>
   <i> the black market."</i>

20:20.138 --> 20:21.470
       "Copenhagen,"
       it says on the label.

20:21.472 --> 20:24.739
   <i> "It was extremely kind</i>
   <i> and generous of you</i>
   <i> to think of us in this way</i>

20:24.741 --> 20:26.006
       <i> "and we are</i>
       <i> extremely grateful."</i>

20:26.008 --> 20:29.209
             How on earth
             did she order it
             from Copenhagen?

20:29.211 --> 20:30.543
          Heaven knows.

20:30.545 --> 20:31.043
              Wait.

20:31.045 --> 20:37.249
 <i> "Best wishes for 1950.</i>
 <i> Yours faithfully, Frank Doel,</i>
 <i> for Marks & Co."</i>

20:37.251 --> 20:38.683
             (KNOCKING)

20:40.153 --> 20:41.819
             Can I help you?
     Yes, please.

20:41.821 --> 20:43.086
 Do you have
 any color prints?

20:43.088 --> 20:46.355
 A man,
 I can't remember his name,
 he does pictures of people.

20:46.357 --> 20:50.726
   They're composed of objects,
   you know, fruit, flowers,

20:50.728 --> 20:52.627
        cauliflowers, cabbages.
        The faces.

20:52.629 --> 20:57.398
          18th or 19th century.
          French, I think.

20:57.633 --> 20:59.833
             Sort of grotesque.

20:59.835 --> 21:03.102
     Very highly colored, um...

21:03.104 --> 21:05.104
     Sort of fruit
     and vegetables?

21:05.106 --> 21:05.871
                         Yes.

21:05.873 --> 21:06.905
 Ah, Giuseppe Arcimboldo.

21:06.907 --> 21:09.140
                  Arcimboldo!
                  Yes! Yes!
                  That's right.

21:09.142 --> 21:10.574
                Do you have any
                of his work?

21:10.576 --> 21:12.275
           Ah!

21:12.277 --> 21:14.443
        Well... Hmm.

21:28.859 --> 21:30.758
                 Hello, Willie.
                 How are you?

21:30.760 --> 21:32.359
     Hello,
     hello.

21:32.861 --> 21:33.960
                  Let's see.
                  I know I want

21:33.962 --> 21:38.431
  four slices of pepper salami,
  four slices of Swiss cheese

21:38.433 --> 21:40.299
              and a quarter of
              a pound of bacon.

21:40.301 --> 21:42.768
  We're out of
  pepper salami.

21:42.770 --> 21:44.069
                 You're out of
                 pepper salami?

21:44.071 --> 21:47.305
   Nobody likes
   pepper salami.

21:47.407 --> 21:48.773
                 I like
                 pepper salami.

21:48.775 --> 21:51.809
 So I should buy it
 special for you?

21:53.813 --> 21:55.512
                       Why not?

21:56.448 --> 21:58.181
        I'm your best customer.

21:58.183 --> 21:59.715
                   (SCOFFS)

21:59.717 --> 22:03.585
           All right, I'm not
           your best customer.

22:07.757 --> 22:12.626
 <i> HELENE: "Frank Doel,</i>
 <i> what are you doing over there?</i>

22:12.628 --> 22:13.727
  <i> "You are not doing anything.</i>

22:13.729 --> 22:19.532
  <i> "You're just sitting around!</i>
  <i> Where is Leigh Hunt?</i>
  <i> Where is the</i> Oxford Verse?

22:19.534 --> 22:24.136
     <i> "Where is the</i> Vulgate
     <i> and dear goofy</i>
     <i> John Henry Newman?</i>

22:24.138 --> 22:27.939
  <i> "I thought they'd be</i>
  <i> such nice uplifting reading</i>
  <i> for Lent,</i>

22:27.941 --> 22:31.042
  <i> "and nothing do you send me!</i>

22:33.479 --> 22:36.446
    <i> "You leave me sitting here</i>
    <i> writing long margin notes</i>

22:36.448 --> 22:38.848
      <i> "in library books that</i>
      <i> don't belong to me.</i>

22:38.850 --> 22:44.119
<i> "Someday</i>
<i> they'll find out I did it</i>
<i> and take my library card away.</i>

22:44.121 --> 22:46.287
        (SIRENS WAILING)

23:10.413 --> 23:15.482
     <i> "I require</i>
     <i> a book of love poems,</i>
     <i> with spring coming on.</i>

23:15.484 --> 23:16.683
     <i> "No Keats or Shelley.</i>

23:16.685 --> 23:20.720
      <i> "Send me poets</i>
      <i> who can make love</i>
      <i> without slobbering.</i>

23:20.722 --> 23:24.290
 <i> "Wyatt or Jonson or somebody.</i>
 <i> Use your own judgment.</i>
 <i> Just a nice book.</i>

23:24.292 --> 23:31.563
  <i> "Preferably small enough</i>
  <i> to stick in a slacks pocket</i>
  <i> and take to Central Park.</i>

23:34.200 --> 23:36.633
   <i> "Well, don't just sit there!</i>
   <i> Go and find it!</i>

23:36.635 --> 23:41.804
   <i> "I swear I don't know</i>
   <i> how that shop keeps going."</i>

23:45.276 --> 23:46.241
                     (LAUGHING)

23:46.243 --> 23:47.575
                 Beautiful set,
                 is it not?

23:47.577 --> 23:49.209
 Yes, very nice,
 yeah.

23:49.211 --> 23:52.845
                  Have you got
                  the catalog
                  of the Du%rer?

23:54.515 --> 23:56.948
         Yes.

24:00.186 --> 24:02.286
   <i> CECILY: "Dear Miss Hanff."</i>

24:02.288 --> 24:02.853
                 Here you are.

24:02.855 --> 24:06.122
   <i> "Please don't let</i>
   <i> Frank know I'm writing this.</i>

24:06.124 --> 24:11.293
   <i> "But every time I send you</i>
   <i> a bill, I've been dying</i>
   <i> to slip in a little note,</i>

24:11.295 --> 24:15.697
    <i> "and he might not think it</i>
    <i> quite proper of me.</i>

24:15.699 --> 24:17.932
       <i> "That sounds stuffy,</i>
       <i> and he's not.</i>

24:17.934 --> 24:21.769
    <i> "He's quite nice, really.</i>
    <i> Very nice, in fact.</i>

24:21.771 --> 24:25.539
 <i> "It's just that</i>
 <i> he does rather look on you</i>
 <i> as his private correspondent,</i>

24:25.541 --> 24:28.708
  <i> "as all your letters and</i>
  <i> parcels are addressed to him.</i>

24:28.710 --> 24:31.777
   <i> "But I just thought</i>
   <i> I'd write to you on my own."</i>

24:31.779 --> 24:32.444
          (PIANO PLAYING)

24:32.446 --> 24:36.147
  HELENE: (READING) "But I just
  thought I'd write to you
  on my own if you don't mind.

24:36.149 --> 24:41.218
      "We all love your letters
      and try to imagine
      what you must be like.

24:41.220 --> 24:43.620
              "I've decided
              that you're young

24:43.622 --> 24:47.857
     "and very sophisticated
     and smart-looking."

24:47.859 --> 24:49.592
                     (LAUGHING)

24:49.594 --> 24:51.327
        What's so funny?

24:52.196 --> 24:55.463
 "Old Mr. Martin thinks
 you must be
 quite studious-looking

24:55.465 --> 24:58.132
 "in spite of your
 wonderful sense of humor.

24:58.134 --> 25:00.100
 "Why don't you send us
 a snapshot?"

25:00.102 --> 25:01.668
                 Why don't you?

25:01.670 --> 25:04.237
  For the first time in my life
  I'm a woman of mystery.

25:04.239 --> 25:08.741
 I'm going to keep it that way.
 "If you're curious
 about Frank..."

25:08.743 --> 25:10.042
                 Which you are.

25:10.044 --> 25:14.613
 "...he's in his late 30s,
 quite nice-looking..."
                   Ooh.

25:14.615 --> 25:17.616
 "...married to
 a very sweet Irish girl."
                          Oh!

25:17.618 --> 25:21.987
     "I believe
     she's his second wife."

25:22.456 --> 25:25.023
 Be ready for Act 2,
 Miss Bellamy.

25:25.025 --> 25:27.125
             Thank you, Elliot.

25:27.660 --> 25:29.192
                       Oh, God.

25:30.461 --> 25:31.493
                     It stinks.

25:31.495 --> 25:32.026
            (BOTH LAUGHING)

25:32.028 --> 25:36.131
 I'll call you, take care.
 I'll call you on Friday.

25:36.133 --> 25:37.265
            See you, then.
  All right.

25:37.267 --> 25:40.034
     <i> CECILY: "Everyone was so</i>
     <i> grateful for the parcel.</i>

25:40.036 --> 25:45.339
   <i> "My little ones, girl, five,</i>
   <i> boy, four, were in heaven.</i>

25:45.341 --> 25:51.578
   <i> "With the raisins and egg,</i>
   <i> I was actually able</i>
   <i> to make them a cake.</i>

25:52.280 --> 25:54.613
    <i> "I do hope you don't mind</i>
    <i> my writing.</i>

25:54.615 --> 25:59.117
    <i> "Please don't mention it</i>
    <i> when you write to Frank."</i>

26:01.354 --> 26:03.287
                        Cecily,

26:03.455 --> 26:04.921
                  are you busy?

26:04.923 --> 26:05.521
             No.

26:05.523 --> 26:07.856
                 We ought to do
                 some letters.

26:07.858 --> 26:09.691
        Yes, coming.

26:13.430 --> 26:17.331
        <i> "With best wishes,</i>
        <i> Cecily Farr."</i>

26:19.868 --> 26:24.103
      <i> HELENE: "Dear Cecily</i>
      <i> and a very bad cess</i>
      <i> to old Mr. Martin.</i>

26:24.105 --> 26:28.173
  <i> "Tell him I'm so unstudious,</i>
  <i> I never even went to college.</i>

26:28.175 --> 26:31.309
    <i> "I just happen to have</i>
    <i> a peculiar taste in books.</i>

26:31.311 --> 26:36.180
   <i> "And I'm about</i>
   <i> as smart-looking</i>
   <i> as a Broadway panhandler.</i>

26:36.182 --> 26:38.582
 <i> "I live in moth-eaten sweaters</i>
 <i> and wool slacks.</i>

26:38.584 --> 26:40.750
  <i> "They don't give us</i>
  <i> any heat here in the daytime.</i>

26:40.752 --> 26:45.121
<i> "It's a five-storey brownstone</i>
<i> and all the other tenants</i>
<i> go out to work at 9:00 a.m.</i>

26:45.123 --> 26:46.755
       <i> "and don't come home</i>
       <i> till 6:00.</i>

26:46.757 --> 26:49.557
  <i> "Why should the landlord heat</i>
  <i> the building for one small</i>

26:49.559 --> 26:53.928
      <i> "script reader/writer</i>
      <i> working at home?"</i>

26:53.930 --> 26:56.931
          Oh, I'm Ed.
          This is Ginny.

26:56.933 --> 26:59.166
                       Hi.
 Hello. Helene.

26:59.168 --> 27:03.570
        Hi. Okay, Helene,
        lead the way.

27:04.940 --> 27:07.006
                   Do you live
                   around here?

27:07.008 --> 27:07.339
                    No.

27:07.341 --> 27:10.942
    But actually, we're looking
    for somewhere.
    We're getting married soon.

27:10.944 --> 27:12.276
  Ooh! How nice!

27:12.278 --> 27:15.979
 What kind of a place
 are you looking for?
 Something fancy?

27:15.981 --> 27:17.246
    Well, I wouldn't say fancy.

27:17.248 --> 27:20.749
 Two or three bedrooms,
 you know. Somewhere
 big enough for a family.

27:20.751 --> 27:23.651
   Ginny would like a place
   overlooking the park.

27:23.653 --> 27:25.252
                 Oh, that
                 would be nice.

27:25.254 --> 27:26.853
   How many rooms
   have you got?

27:26.855 --> 27:32.558
 Oh, well I have a workroom
 and a sitting room and
 a bedroom

27:32.560 --> 27:36.194
            and a dining room
            and a kitchen.

27:36.196 --> 27:38.896
             And here it is.

27:38.898 --> 27:40.464
          (ALL LAUGHING)

27:40.466 --> 27:42.299
            Kettle's on.

27:55.180 --> 27:57.980
   <i> HELENE: "Poor Frank,</i>
   <i> I give him such a hard time.</i>

27:57.982 --> 27:59.881
   <i> "I'm always bawling him out</i>
   <i> for something.</i>

27:59.883 --> 28:03.017
  <i> "I'm only teasing, but I know</i>
  <i> he'll take me seriously.</i>

28:03.019 --> 28:07.254
   <i> "I keep trying to puncture</i>
   <i> that proper British reserve.</i>

28:07.256 --> 28:09.422
<i> "If he gets ulcers, I did it."</i>

28:09.424 --> 28:10.356
           (LAUGHING)

28:10.358 --> 28:12.224
       (TOILET FLUSHING)

28:19.766 --> 28:22.266
                  How's the tea
                  coming along?

28:22.268 --> 28:24.167
 It's almost ready.

28:26.371 --> 28:30.339
       What would we do without
       our cups of tea?

28:30.341 --> 28:35.444
                 Life would be
                 insupportable,
                 would it not?

28:38.549 --> 28:40.448
      <i> MAN ON PA:</i>
      <i> The train from Ketchworth</i>

28:40.450 --> 28:44.685
          <i> is now arriving</i>
          <i> at Platform 3.</i>

28:44.687 --> 28:47.020
  <i> (SLOW MUSIC PLAYING IN FILM)</i>

28:51.326 --> 28:52.858
              <i> MAN: Forgive me.</i>

28:52.860 --> 28:53.925
  <i> WOMAN: Forgive you</i>
  <i> for what?</i>

28:53.927 --> 28:58.396
           <i> For everything.</i>
           <i> For meeting you</i>
           <i> in the first place.</i>

28:58.398 --> 29:01.999
     <i> (WHISTLE BLOWING)</i>
     <i> For taking a piece of grit</i>
     <i> out of your eye.</i>

29:02.001 --> 29:03.066
               <i> For loving you.</i>

29:03.068 --> 29:06.502
               <i> For bringing you</i>
               <i> so much misery.</i>

29:06.504 --> 29:07.603
     <i> (TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)</i>

29:07.605 --> 29:11.373
  <i> I'll forgive you if</i>
  <i> you'll forgive me.</i>

29:19.182 --> 29:19.980
                <i> MAN: Thursday.</i>

29:19.982 --> 29:22.649
    <i> HELENE: "Please write</i>
    <i> and tell me about London.</i>

29:22.651 --> 29:25.251
    <i> "I live for the day when</i>
    <i> I step off the boat-train</i>

29:25.253 --> 29:28.921
  <i> "and feel its dirty sidewalks</i>
  <i> under my feet.</i>

29:29.023 --> 29:33.425
    <i> "I want to walk up</i>
    <i> Berkeley Square</i>
    <i> and down Wimpole Street</i>

29:33.427 --> 29:36.761
    <i> "and stand in St. Paul's</i>
    <i> where John Donne preached,</i>

29:36.763 --> 29:38.896
       <i> "and sit on the step</i>
       <i> Elizabeth sat on</i>

29:38.898 --> 29:43.800
     <i> "when she refused</i>
     <i> to enter the Tower,</i>
     <i> and places like that.</i>

29:44.169 --> 29:45.434
    <i> "A newspaper man I know,</i>

29:45.436 --> 29:47.836
   <i> "who was stationed in London</i>
   <i> during the war, says</i>

29:47.838 --> 29:51.239
    <i> "tourists go to England</i>
    <i> with preconceived notions,</i>

29:51.241 --> 29:55.710
   <i> "so they always find exactly</i>
   <i> what they go looking for.</i>

29:55.712 --> 30:00.214
<i> "I told him I'd go looking for</i>
<i> the England of</i>
<i> English literature.</i>

30:00.216 --> 30:04.017
       <i> "And he said,</i>
       <i> 'Then, it's there.'"</i>

30:08.023 --> 30:08.888
    <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>

30:08.890 --> 30:11.690
    <i> "This is to let you know</i>
    <i> that we now have in stock</i>

30:11.692 --> 30:13.992
       "The Oxford Book
       of English Verse."

30:13.994 --> 30:14.993
              It's quite
              a nice Jonson.

30:14.995 --> 30:20.865
  <i> "Printed on India paper,</i>
  <i> original blue cloth binding,</i>
  <i> 1905.</i>

30:20.867 --> 30:26.070
    <i> "Inscription in ink</i>
    <i> on the flyleaf, but</i>
    <i> a good second-hand copy.</i>

30:26.072 --> 30:28.372
         <i> "Price, $2."</i>

30:28.374 --> 30:28.872
                    Swinburne.

30:28.874 --> 30:30.874
  <i> "We thought we'd better quote</i>
  <i> before sending,</i>

30:30.876 --> 30:34.344
    <i> "in case you have already</i>
    <i> purchased a copy."</i>

30:34.346 --> 30:36.379
        Hardy, limited edition.

30:36.381 --> 30:38.647
     Very nice.

30:41.685 --> 30:42.350
         (EXCLAIMS)

30:42.352 --> 30:47.288
   <i> "Some time ago</i>
   <i> you asked us for Newman's</i>
   Idea of a University."

30:47.290 --> 30:47.988
  Very nice indeed.

30:47.990 --> 30:51.157
     <i> "Would you be</i>
     <i> interested in a copy</i>
     <i> of the first edition?"</i>

30:51.159 --> 30:54.527
       We'll put that one aside
       for Miss Hanff.

30:54.996 --> 31:00.199
         He has a first edition
        of Newman's <i> University</i>
         for six bucks!

31:00.201 --> 31:03.535
         Do I want it,
         he asks innocently.

31:04.638 --> 31:06.638
             (SIGHING)

31:07.974 --> 31:09.873
      <i> HELENE: "Dear Frank.</i>

31:09.875 --> 31:11.975
       <i> "Yes, I want it."</i>

31:11.977 --> 31:12.709
     Bye-bye.
                 Bye-bye.

31:12.711 --> 31:15.745
       <i> "I won't be fit</i>
       <i> to live with myself.</i>

31:16.180 --> 31:18.580
     <i> "I've never cared about</i>
     <i> first editions per se,</i>

31:18.582 --> 31:22.817
       <i> "but a first edition</i>
       <i> of that book!"</i>

31:31.394 --> 31:31.959
             <i> "Well!</i>

31:31.961 --> 31:35.395
    <i> "All I have to say to you,</i>
    <i> Frank Doel,</i>

31:35.397 --> 31:38.965
    <i> "is we live in depraved,</i>
    <i> destructive and</i>
    <i> degenerate times</i>

31:38.967 --> 31:40.866
        <i> "when a bookshop,</i>
        <i> a bookshop,</i>

31:40.868 --> 31:45.570
  <i> "starts tearing up beautiful</i>
  <i> old books to use</i>
  <i> as wrapping paper.</i>

31:45.572 --> 31:50.207
  <i> "What's worse is,</i>
  <i> you tore the book up in</i>
  <i> the middle of a major battle</i>

31:50.209 --> 31:53.343
      <i> "and I don't even know</i>
      <i> which war it was!"</i>

31:53.345 --> 31:54.644
               Thank you.

31:54.646 --> 31:59.148
 HELENE: Take a look at this.
 Isn't that beautiful?

31:59.150 --> 32:00.616
           It's beautiful.

32:00.618 --> 32:05.153
    It's a first edition,
    my dear.
    100 years old.

32:05.155 --> 32:06.721
          It's beautiful.

32:06.723 --> 32:08.289
          I feel kind of guilty
          about owning it.

32:08.291 --> 32:11.025
      All that gleaming leather
      and gold stamping.

32:11.027 --> 32:15.396
  It belongs
  in a pine panel library
  in some English country home.

32:15.398 --> 32:17.965
          You know what I mean?

32:17.967 --> 32:21.802
 It should be read by the fire,
 in a gentleman's
 leather easy chair,

32:21.804 --> 32:27.407
  not in some second-hand
  overstuffed seat in a
  broken-down brownstone front.

32:27.409 --> 32:32.278
 Oh, now, if I was this book,
 I'd want to live right here.

32:38.352 --> 32:40.151
                 You're right.

32:40.987 --> 32:41.485
                  Right.

32:41.487 --> 32:46.122
   <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>
   <i> I'm sorry for the delay</i>
   <i> in answering your letter,</i>

32:46.124 --> 32:48.624
   <i> "I've been away out of town</i>
   <i> for a week or so.</i>

32:48.626 --> 32:52.394
     <i> "I'm now busy</i>
     <i> trying to catch up</i>
     <i> on my correspondence."</i>

32:52.396 --> 32:53.995
                   Let me see.

32:54.897 --> 32:56.863
        There, you look lovely.

32:56.865 --> 32:57.263
    (LAUGHS)

32:57.265 --> 32:58.864
   <i> "First of all,</i>
   <i> please don't worry about us</i>

32:58.866 --> 33:02.534
    <i> "using old books such as</i>
    <i> Clarendon's</i> Rebellion
    <i> for wrapping."</i>

33:02.536 --> 33:04.569
      Come on, Mary,
      you can wear it tomorrow.

33:04.571 --> 33:05.503
   <i> "In this particular case,</i>

33:05.505 --> 33:10.007
   <i> "they were just</i>
   <i> two odd volumes</i>
   <i> with the covers detached.</i>

33:10.009 --> 33:15.846
 <i> "Nobody in their right senses</i>
 <i> would have given us</i>
 <i> a shilling for them."</i>

33:15.848 --> 33:17.881
               NORA: Thank you.

33:18.016 --> 33:18.981
                Now, jump in.

33:18.983 --> 33:20.015
 I'll see to that.

33:20.017 --> 33:21.516
           Thanks. Night-night.

33:21.518 --> 33:23.951
      <i> "We are glad you liked</i>
     <i> the</i> Q Anthology.

33:23.953 --> 33:28.689
  <i> "We have no copy of the</i>
  Oxford Book of English Prose
  <i> in stock at the moment,</i>

33:28.691 --> 33:31.758
        <i> "but will try to</i>
        <i> find one for you.</i>

33:31.760 --> 33:33.192
      <i> "There are five of us</i>
      <i> in the shop,</i>

33:33.194 --> 33:37.296
    <i> "not including</i>
    <i> Mr. Marks and Mr. Cohen."</i>

33:37.364 --> 33:39.397
         Bye.
              See you later.

33:39.399 --> 33:40.231
                     Yes.

33:40.233 --> 33:42.032
          Have a nice time.

33:42.401 --> 33:44.701
       (JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

34:15.400 --> 34:16.931
 Are you enjoying yourself,
 Frank?

34:16.934 --> 34:18.934
               Yeah. When did
               we last do this?

34:18.936 --> 34:20.568
 I don't remember.

34:20.570 --> 34:22.536
                 Neither do I.

34:25.774 --> 34:27.306
                 That's lovely.

34:27.308 --> 34:28.873
          (MUSIC STOPS)

34:29.543 --> 34:32.409
  Let's go and
  look at the river.

34:32.411 --> 34:33.878
        (ALL CHATTERING)

34:39.217 --> 34:40.684
  Lovely.
           Lovely.

34:40.686 --> 34:42.418
     <i> (MAN CHATTERING ON PA)</i>
 Look at the lights.

34:42.420 --> 34:45.288
    We should dance more often.
    We don't go enough, do we?

34:45.290 --> 34:47.223
     (SIGHS)
     I can't.

34:47.324 --> 34:48.524
     I can't.
        That's nonsense.

34:48.525 --> 34:51.293
 Look at that,
 isn't that the Savoy?

34:51.295 --> 34:51.926
        No, that's the Shell.

34:51.928 --> 34:54.561
         Isn't that
         the Shell building?
     Shell?

34:54.763 --> 34:55.628
      (MUSIC STARTS AGAIN)

34:55.630 --> 34:58.130
      Oh no.
          Oh, look.
          Oh, come on.

34:58.132 --> 34:59.664
        It's a long time
        since we've done that.

34:59.666 --> 35:03.801
 I can't. I can't dance.
 All right, once more.

35:11.944 --> 35:14.377
       (PEOPLE WHOOPING)

35:33.998 --> 35:35.931
         (ALL CHEERING)

35:47.444 --> 35:48.176
                 You look good.

35:48.178 --> 35:49.377
    You look so beautiful!
                     Thank you.

35:49.379 --> 35:54.215
 Have lots of babies!
 I'll come babysit okay?
 Have a dog, too!

35:54.217 --> 35:55.783
                   We will.

35:56.119 --> 35:57.551
                  Bye!

35:57.653 --> 36:00.286
        (BRIAN SINGING)

36:00.288 --> 36:02.254
        (PEOPLE LAUGHING)

36:06.960 --> 36:09.026
                  Bravo. Bravo.

36:09.028 --> 36:11.428
              Helene,
              you are amazing!

36:11.430 --> 36:12.796
      Yes. Yes, I am.

36:12.798 --> 36:14.364
                 I drink to...
            I can't believe it.

36:14.366 --> 36:19.168
    I drink to you and the best
    looking Yorkshire pudding,
    this side of the Atlantic.

36:19.170 --> 36:23.405
     To Helene
     and the Yorkshire pudding.

36:25.008 --> 36:26.474
              Cheers!

36:28.010 --> 36:30.777
    Happy birthday, Brian.
    Bon voyage, Maxine.

36:30.779 --> 36:35.348
 Now, why you're going to
 England and I'm not,
 God only knows!

36:35.350 --> 36:36.782
                     (LAUGHING)

36:38.452 --> 36:43.621
     <i> HELENE: "Dear Cecily.</i>
     <i> Yorkshire pudding,</i>
     <i> out of this world.</i>

36:43.623 --> 36:44.555
   <i> "We have nothing like it.</i>

36:44.557 --> 36:45.789
      <i> "I had to describe it</i>
      <i> to somebody</i>

36:45.791 --> 36:50.460
           (PHONE RINGING)
       <i> "as a high, curved,</i>
       <i> smooth, empty waffle."</i>

36:50.462 --> 36:52.528
              Helene Hanff.

36:55.299 --> 36:56.798
                 What?

36:57.867 --> 36:58.465
              Who is this?

36:58.467 --> 37:03.336
 <i> "A producer who likes</i>
 <i> my plays, but not enough</i>
 <i> to produce them, just phoned.</i>

37:03.338 --> 37:08.641
  <i> "He's producing a TV series.</i>
  <i> Do I want to write</i>
  <i> for television?</i>

37:08.643 --> 37:11.377
       <i> "'Two bills,'</i>
       <i> he said carelessly."</i>

37:11.379 --> 37:14.246
      "Two bills." What do you
      mean, "Two bills"?

37:14.248 --> 37:18.850
      <i> "It turns out he meant</i>
      <i> $200 a script!</i>

37:18.852 --> 37:22.520
      <i> "And me, a $40-a-week</i>
      <i> script reader!</i>

37:22.522 --> 37:24.455
       <i> "I go down</i>
       <i> to see him tomorrow."</i>

37:24.457 --> 37:28.025
          10:30? Sure, yes,
          I'll be there.

37:28.027 --> 37:31.695
            See you then.
            Thanks.

37:35.500 --> 37:36.832
                (SIGHS)

37:37.801 --> 37:40.735
   <i> "Keep your fingers crossed.</i>

37:40.837 --> 37:43.604
          <i> "Best, Helene."</i>

37:44.073 --> 37:45.405
              Oh.

37:45.407 --> 37:47.440
           Boy, oh boy.

37:52.046 --> 37:54.846
         Boy, oh boy,
         oh boy, oh boy...

38:01.955 --> 38:08.159
            There we are.
            Pork sausages,
            and raisins.

38:10.096 --> 38:11.929
               Now, Megan.

38:11.931 --> 38:16.700
         Peaches. And...
         Got some ham.

38:18.837 --> 38:19.535
    <i> MEGAN: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>

38:19.537 --> 38:24.306
 <i> "This is just to let you know</i>
 <i> that your Easter parcels to</i>
 <i> Marks & Co. arrived safely</i>

38:24.308 --> 38:25.073
           <i> "a few days ago.</i>

38:25.075 --> 38:28.910
    <i> "We were all quite dazzled</i>
    <i> to see the meat.</i>

38:28.912 --> 38:32.213
      <i> "And the eggs and tins</i>
      <i> were so very welcome.</i>

38:32.215 --> 38:37.017
  <i> "I did feel I must write and</i>
  <i> tell you how exceedingly</i>
  <i> grateful we all are</i>

38:37.019 --> 38:40.387
        <i> "for your kindness</i>
        <i> and generosity."</i>

38:45.694 --> 38:46.592
           (CAT MEOWS)

38:46.594 --> 38:49.428
         My word,
         this looks good.

38:49.797 --> 38:51.797
     CECILY: Michael, Ann!

38:51.799 --> 38:53.431
   <i> CECILY: "My dear, the meat!</i>

38:53.433 --> 38:57.168
     <i> "I really don't think</i>
     <i> you should spend</i>
     <i> your money like that.</i>

38:57.170 --> 38:59.637
           <i> "It must have</i>
           <i> cost a packet!"</i>

38:59.639 --> 39:00.371
                It's sausages!

39:00.373 --> 39:02.539
       <i> "Bless you</i>
       <i> for your kind heart."</i>

39:02.541 --> 39:05.775
     Do you know who sent them?
     You remember the lady...

39:09.213 --> 39:12.247
     <i> BILL: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>
     <i> For nearly two years</i>

39:12.249 --> 39:16.217
    <i> "I've been working as a</i>
    <i> cataloguer at Marks & Co.</i>

39:16.219 --> 39:18.285
       <i> "and would like to</i>
       <i> thank you very much</i>

39:18.287 --> 39:23.123
   <i> "for my share-out in the</i>
   <i> parcels you've been sending.</i>

39:23.125 --> 39:28.595
    <i> "I live with my great aunt,</i>
    <i> who is 75."</i>

39:28.763 --> 39:31.130
        BILL: Do please look,
        Auntie.

39:31.132 --> 39:31.930
       <i> "And I think that</i>

39:31.932 --> 39:35.700
  <i> "if you had seen the look of</i>
  <i> delight on her face when I</i>
  <i> brought home the meat</i>

39:35.702 --> 39:41.138
   <i> "and the tin of tongue,</i>
   <i> you would have realized</i>
   <i> just how grateful we are."</i>

39:41.140 --> 39:45.509
 I don't like the idea
 of that tin coming
 all the way from America.

39:45.511 --> 39:49.179
          It's only come
          from Denmark, Auntie.

39:49.681 --> 39:54.450
  <i> "It's certainly good to know</i>
  <i> that someone</i>
  <i> so many miles away</i>

39:54.452 --> 39:59.688
    <i> "can be so kind</i>
    <i> and generous to people</i>
    <i> they haven't even seen.</i>

39:59.690 --> 40:02.490
   <i> "And I think that everyone</i>
   <i> in the firm feels the same.</i>

40:02.492 --> 40:08.295
  <i> "If at any time you know of</i>
  <i> anything that you would like</i>
  <i> sent over from London,</i>

40:08.297 --> 40:12.032
      <i> "I will be most happy</i>
      <i> to see to it for you.</i>

40:12.034 --> 40:15.201
  <i> "Sincerely, Bill Humphries."</i>

40:16.337 --> 40:17.736
            (SNIFFING)

40:22.375 --> 40:24.041
      (LAUGHING EXCITEDLY)

40:26.645 --> 40:30.546
 What a treat!
 What a treat!

40:45.896 --> 40:47.528
 (SQUEALING EXCITEDLY)

40:50.132 --> 40:53.666
    <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>
    <i> I expect you are</i>
    <i> getting a bit worried</i>

40:53.668 --> 40:56.335
  <i> "that we have not written</i>
  <i> to thank you for your parcels</i>

40:56.337 --> 41:00.839
 <i> "and are probably thinking</i>
 <i> that we are an ungrateful lot.</i>

41:00.841 --> 41:03.808
 <i> "The truth is that I have been</i>
 <i> chasing around the country,</i>

41:03.810 --> 41:06.277
     <i> "in and out of various</i>
     <i> stately homes of England,</i>

41:06.279 --> 41:12.182
   <i> "trying to buy a few books</i>
   <i> to fill up</i>
   <i> our sadly depleted stock.</i>

41:15.053 --> 41:17.953
     <i> "My wife was starting to</i>
     <i> call me 'The Lodger,'</i>

41:17.955 --> 41:19.187
      <i> "just went home</i>
      <i> for bed and breakfast.</i>

41:19.189 --> 41:22.924
   <i> "But of course</i>
   <i> when I arrived home</i>
   <i> with a nice piece of meat,</i>

41:22.926 --> 41:24.892
        <i> "to say nothing of</i>
        <i> dried eggs and ham,</i>

41:24.894 --> 41:29.296
     <i> "then she thought</i>
     <i> I was a fine fellow,</i>
     <i> and all was forgiven.</i>

41:29.298 --> 41:34.534
    <i> "It is a long time since</i>
    <i> we saw so much meat</i>
    <i> all in one piece."</i>

41:37.772 --> 41:41.540
   Lots 40 through to 49 are on
   the next landing, sir.
                  Thank you.

41:41.542 --> 41:42.841
                  Good morning,
                  John.

41:42.843 --> 41:44.809
   Good morning.

41:45.778 --> 41:47.244
                  Oh, yes.

41:55.454 --> 41:59.355
    <i> "We should like to</i>
    <i> express our appreciation</i>
    <i> in some way or other</i>

41:59.357 --> 42:02.725
        <i> "so we are sending</i>
        <i> by book post today</i>

42:02.727 --> 42:06.061
   <i> "a little book</i>
   <i> which I hope you will like.</i>

42:06.063 --> 42:11.766
  <i> "I remember you asked me</i>
  <i> for a volume of Elizabethan</i>
  <i> love poems some time ago.</i>

42:11.768 --> 42:16.637
    <i> "Well, this is the nearest</i>
    <i> I can get to it."</i>

42:34.657 --> 42:40.260
 <i> FRANK: "To Helene Hanff,</i>
 <i> with best wishes and grateful</i>
 <i> thanks for many kindnesses</i>

42:40.262 --> 42:47.600
 <i> "from all at</i>
 <i> 84 Charing Cross Road.</i>
 <i> London, April, 1951."</i>

42:52.807 --> 42:54.273
                       God.

42:57.111 --> 43:01.346
      <i> HELENE: "To all at</i>
      <i> 84 Charing Cross Road.</i>

43:01.614 --> 43:03.847
       <i> "Thank you for this</i>
       <i> beautiful book.</i>

43:03.849 --> 43:08.084
    <i> "I've never owned a book</i>
    <i> before with pages</i>
    <i> edged all round in gold.</i>

43:08.086 --> 43:12.321
    <i> "Would you believe</i>
    <i> it arrived on my birthday?</i>

43:12.323 --> 43:17.626
  <i> "I wish you hadn't been so</i>
  <i> over-courteous about putting</i>
  <i> the inscription on a card</i>

43:17.628 --> 43:19.894
  <i> "instead of on the flyleaf.</i>

43:19.896 --> 43:21.896
      <i> "It's the bookseller</i>
      <i> coming out in you all.</i>

43:21.898 --> 43:24.865
    <i> "You were afraid</i>
    <i> you'd decrease its value.</i>

43:24.867 --> 43:28.001
   <i> "You would have increased it</i>
   <i> for the present owner</i>

43:28.003 --> 43:31.137
        <i> "and possibly</i>
        <i> for future owners.</i>

43:31.139 --> 43:35.074
     <i> "I love inscriptions</i>
     <i> on flyleaves</i>
     <i> and notes in margins.</i>

43:35.076 --> 43:38.877
  <i> "I like the comradely sense</i>
  <i> of turning pages</i>
  <i> someone else turned</i>

43:38.879 --> 43:44.682
  <i> "and reading passages</i>
  <i> someone long gone</i>
  <i> has called my attention to.</i>

43:44.684 --> 43:46.984
       <i> "And why didn't you</i>
       <i> sign your names?</i>

43:46.986 --> 43:48.418
        <i> "I expect Frank</i>
        <i> wouldn't let you.</i>

43:48.420 --> 43:53.990
  <i> "He probably doesn't want me</i>
  <i> writing love letters</i>
  <i> to anyone but him."</i>

43:58.896 --> 44:03.465
  <i> MAXINE: "Dear Heart.</i>
  <i> It's the loveliest old shop,</i>
  <i> straight out of Dickens.</i>

44:03.467 --> 44:07.602
    <i> "You would go absolutely</i>
    <i> out of your mind over it.</i>

44:07.604 --> 44:08.536
   <i> "There are stalls outside</i>

44:08.538 --> 44:10.237
    <i> "and I stopped and leafed</i>
    <i> through a few things</i>

44:10.239 --> 44:14.741
     <i> "just to establish myself</i>
     <i> as a browser</i>
     <i> before wandering in.</i>

44:31.159 --> 44:32.258
       <i> "It's dim inside.</i>

44:32.260 --> 44:35.361
    <i> "You can smell the shop</i>
    <i> before you see it.</i>
    <i> It's a lovely smell.</i>

44:35.363 --> 44:40.666
 <i> "I can't articulate it easily</i>
 <i> but it combines must and dust</i>
 <i> and age</i>

44:40.668 --> 44:43.235
       <i> "and walls of wood</i>
       <i> and floors of wood.</i>

44:43.237 --> 44:48.139
  <i> "Toward the back of the shop</i>
  <i> at the left, there's a desk</i>
  <i> with a work lamp on it.</i>

44:48.141 --> 44:51.342
       <i> "A man was sitting there</i>
       <i> with a Hogarth nose.</i>

44:51.344 --> 44:53.877
    <i> "He looked up and said..."</i>

44:53.879 --> 44:57.280
           So sorry.
           Good afternoon.

44:57.615 --> 44:59.848
      Would you like some help?

45:00.050 --> 45:00.915
            May I look around?

45:00.917 --> 45:04.084
  Oh, yes. Of course.
  Please do.

45:11.159 --> 45:12.391
  <i> "The shelves go on forever.</i>

45:12.393 --> 45:18.029
   <i> "They go up to the ceiling</i>
   <i> and they're very old</i>
   <i> and kind of grey,</i>

45:18.031 --> 45:21.932
   <i> "like old oak that absorbed</i>
   <i> so much dust over the years,</i>

45:21.934 --> 45:24.534
      <i> "they no longer</i>
      <i> are their true color.</i>

45:24.536 --> 45:25.535
   <i> "There's a print selection,</i>

45:25.537 --> 45:31.240
<i> "or rather a long print table,</i>
<i> with Cruikshank and Rackham</i>
<i> and Spy</i>

45:31.242 --> 45:35.310
<i> "and all those</i>
<i> old wonderful English</i>
<i> caricaturists and illustrators</i>

45:35.312 --> 45:38.012
    <i> "that I'm not smart enough</i>
    <i> to know a lot about.</i>

45:38.014 --> 45:44.218
     <i> "And there are</i>
     <i> some lovely old, old</i>
     <i> illustrated magazines.</i>

45:45.287 --> 45:47.954
        <i> "I stayed for about</i>
        <i> half an hour</i>
        <i> hoping your Frank</i>

45:47.956 --> 45:50.456
     <i> "or one of the girls</i>
     <i> would turn up, but it was</i>
     <i> 1:00 when I went in.</i>

45:50.458 --> 45:56.562
 <i> "I gathered they were all</i>
 <i> out to lunch, and I couldn't</i>
 <i> stay any longer."</i>

46:04.872 --> 46:09.741
 What kind of a <i> Pepys' Diary</i>

46:09.743 --> 46:13.077
             do you call this?

46:13.913 --> 46:15.712
                This is not

46:16.514 --> 46:20.249
              <i> Pepys' Diary.</i>

46:20.251 --> 46:24.186
         This is some busybody

46:24.421 --> 46:28.122
           editor's collection

46:28.124 --> 46:30.824
               of excerpts

46:30.826 --> 46:35.728
           from <i> Pepys' Diary.</i>

46:36.664 --> 46:38.430
                May he rot.

46:38.498 --> 46:42.299
           I could just spit.

47:07.626 --> 47:11.260
                  I enclose

47:12.563 --> 47:17.666
              two limp singles.

47:18.802 --> 47:22.036
             I will make do

47:22.038 --> 47:26.707
     with this until you get me

47:27.376 --> 47:31.511
             a real <i> Pepys.</i>

47:33.282 --> 47:34.848
               Then

47:36.451 --> 47:41.654
             I will rip up

47:41.789 --> 47:44.890
            this ersatz book

47:45.926 --> 47:50.161
              page by page

47:51.164 --> 47:55.499
         and wrap things in it!

48:12.951 --> 48:16.585
     Fresh eggs or
     powdered for Christmas?

48:16.987 --> 48:18.152
        I know the powdered
        lasts longer,

48:18.154 --> 48:24.191
      but fresh farm eggs
      flown in from Denmark
      have got to taste better.

48:24.359 --> 48:26.726
    Want to take a vote on it?

48:26.994 --> 48:30.762
           <i> Vote Pestell and</i>
           <i> keep the Tories out.</i>

48:30.764 --> 48:35.933
    <i> Vote Reg Pestell,</i>
    <i> your Labor Party candidate.</i>

48:35.935 --> 48:40.370
       <i> Vote Pestell</i>
       <i> and keep the Tories out.</i>

48:40.638 --> 48:43.338
<i> (MAN CONTINUES SPEAKING ON PA)</i>

48:53.149 --> 48:54.648
    <i> FRANK: "Dear Miss Hanff.</i>

48:54.650 --> 48:57.617
